        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="left_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>
                        Perge Tacite: nec interrumpatur ha[e]c in Leges Romanas subtilis animaduersio.
                        Ne bello quidem Italico, mox Ciuili omissum, quin multa, et diversa sciscerentur: donec L. Sylla dictator, abolitis uel conuersis prioribus, cum plura 
                        addidisset, otium ei [sic, not eius] rei haud in longum parauit; statim turbidis Lepidi rogationibus. Neq[ue] multò post Tribunis reddita licentia, 
                        quoquò vellent populum agitandi. Iamq[ue] non modò in commune, sed in singulos homines lata[e] qua[e]stiones: et corruptissima Repub[ublica] 
                        plurima[e] Leges. {Qua[e] tandem reformatio? triplex: vna Pompeii: altera Augusti: tertia Tiberij. De quorum remedijs suo loco. 
                        Ergò hinc eliciatur iudicium de Romanis Legibus: et singularum causa[e] interna[e], externa[e] intimè penetrentur. Satis multi de eis conscripserunt, 
                        si satis exquisitè. Delectus faciendus: et sagaci iudicio excutienda singula. Diligentes sunt pla[e]riq[ue] polyhistores: aut curiosi philologi: 
                        vtinam peritiores politici.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Tacitus"/>
                    <person name="Sulla"/>
                    <person name="Marcus Aemilius Lepidus"/>
                    <person name="Pompey"/>
                    <person name="Augustus"/>
                    <person name="Tiberius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Go on, Tacitus, and let this fine comment to the Roman Laws not be interrupted: “Even the Italian and then the Civil war did not pass 
                without the enactment of many conflicting laws, till Lucius Sulla, the Dictator, by the repeal or alteration of past legislation and by many additions, 
                gave us a brief lull in this process, to be instantly followed by the seditious proposals of Lepidus, and soon afterwards by the tribunes recovering 
                their license to excite the people just as they chose. And now bills were passed, not only for national objects but for individual cases, and 
                laws were most numerous when the commonwealth was most corrupt.” What reform, finally, was there? A threefold one: one by Pompey, 
                another by Augustus and the third by Tiberius. For the remedies these presented, [see] at its proper place. Therefore let the judgement of 
                Roman Law be based on this point, and let the internal and external causes of the individual laws be scrutinized thoroughly. 
                Many have written enough about these, if [only?] sufficiently precisely. Discrimination should be practiced and individual issues 
                should be examined with perceptive judgement. Most polyhistors are attentive or careful philologists; if only they would be more skilful politicians.
            </translation>
        </marginalia>
        
